{
  "masechta": "Zevachim",
  "daf": 75,
  "amud": "b",
  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "Introduction to the Daf and the Mishna's List of Disqualified Animals",
      "display_title": "Intro & Pasul Animals",
      "timestamp": "00:11",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Opening remarks and daf orientation",
          "display_title": "Opening",
          "timestamp": "00:11"
        },
        {
          "title": "Overview of the Mishna discussing mixed-up animals and categories of pasul korbanot",
          "display_title": "Mishna Overview",
          "timestamp": "00:33"
        },
        {
          "title": "Explanation of specific disqualifications: roveiah, nirba, muktza, ne'evad, etnan, mechir kelev, kilayim, and treifa",
          "display_title": "Disqualifications",
          "timestamp": "00:43"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Problem of Identifying a Treifa Animal When Mixed with Others",
      "display_title": "Treifa Problem",
      "timestamp": "02:28",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The Gemara's question: how can a treifa animal get mixed up if it has a visible injury?",
          "display_title": "Treifa Mystery",
          "timestamp": "02:28"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yannai's solution: two similarly injured animals (nikuvat hakotz vs. drusat haze'ev) can be confused",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Yannai",
          "timestamp": "03:34"
        },
        {
          "title": "Reish Lakish's solution: a nefulah (fallen) animal requires continued observation (me'et le'et) and post-shechita examination",
          "display_title": "Reish Lakish",
          "timestamp": "05:14"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yirmiya's solution: vlad treifa (offspring of a treifa mother) cannot be visually identified",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Yirmiya",
          "timestamp": "07:02"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Why the Other Amoraim Reject Each Amoraic Opinion",
      "display_title": "Rejections",
      "timestamp": "10:31",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The Gemara explains why Reish Lakish and Rabbi Yirmiya reject Rabbi Yannai: injuries from thorn vs. wolf are visually distinguishable",
          "display_title": "Against Yannai",
          "timestamp": "10:31"
        },
        {
          "title": "Why Rabbi Yannai and Rabbi Yirmiya reject Reish Lakish: they hold that amda (standing up) plus halcha (walking) removes the chazaka of injury without need for prolonged examination",
          "display_title": "Against Lakish",
          "timestamp": "11:35"
        },
        {
          "title": "Why Rabbi Yannai and Reish Lakish reject Rabbi Yirmiya: they do not hold like Rabbi Eliezer that vlad treifa is disqualified",
          "display_title": "Against Yirmiya",
          "timestamp": "12:02"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Mixed Korbanot of the Same Type: the Case of Individual and Communal Sacrifices",
      "display_title": "Korbanot Mix",
      "timestamp": "13:41",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Mishna principle: when korbanot of the same type mix, each one is offered for its respective owner",
          "display_title": "Kodashim Principle",
          "timestamp": "13:41"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara question: how can semichah (laying of hands) be performed if owners cannot identify their animals?",
          "display_title": "Semichah Problem",
          "timestamp": "14:28"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Yosef's resolution: the Mishna speaks only of korban nashim (women's offerings) which do not require semichah",
          "display_title": "Rav Yosef",
          "timestamp": "15:12"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Abaye's Challenge to Rav Yosef and the Rules for Mixed Blood Offerings",
      "display_title": "Abaye Challenge",
      "timestamp": "15:39",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Abaye cites a baraita about mixed korbanot and the application of matanot (portions of blood) when animals are mixed alive vs. after shechita",
          "display_title": "Baraita Cases",
          "timestamp": "15:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's interpretation: the baraita distinguishes between animals mixed while alive (in separate containers) vs. blood mixed together after shechita",
          "display_title": "Rava Interprets",
          "timestamp": "21:19"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi's opinion: examining whether the matanah has sufficient blood volume from each korban to be kasher",
          "display_title": "Rabbi's Volume Test",
          "timestamp": "22:32"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Tosefta on Parah Adumah and Minimal Quantities of Holy Water",
      "display_title": "Parah Rules",
      "timestamp": "23:03",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Citation of Rabbi Eliezer's view that even a drop of mei chatat suffices for purification, with no minimum measure required",
          "display_title": "Eliezer Minimum",
          "timestamp": "23:03"
        },
        {
          "title": "Discussion of how parah adumah may differ from korban blood offerings in terms of the quantity required for a valid matanah",
          "display_title": "Parah vs. Korban",
          "timestamp": "23:49"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Bechor and Ma'aser Mixed with Disqualified Animals: Practical Resolution",
      "display_title": "Bechor Ma'aser",
      "timestamp": "25:01",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Mishna rule: when bechor or ma'aser mix with disqualified animals, they graze until developing a mum, then eaten as disqualified bechor/ma'aser",
          "display_title": "Grazing Till Mum",
          "timestamp": "25:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi bar Chama's questions about bechor restrictions: feeding to niddot, redemption, weighing by litra, and making temurah",
          "display_title": "Bechor Restrictions",
          "timestamp": "25:54"
        },
        {
          "title": "Discussion of whether donating a bechor to bedek habayit creates dual kedusha, with responses from Rav Huna and Rabbi Chizkiya",
          "display_title": "Dual Kedusha",
          "timestamp": "28:03"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Why Only Chatat and Asham Cannot Mix with Other Korbanot",
      "display_title": "Chatat Asham",
      "timestamp": "33:28",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Gemara explores why chatat and asham are exceptions: examination of gender differences and the proposal to distinguish by animal type",
          "display_title": "Gender Distinctions",
          "timestamp": "33:28"
        },
        {
          "title": "Consideration of whether pesach and asham could be mixed, and alternative distinctions by wool vs. hair and by age requirements",
          "display_title": "Age & Type",
          "timestamp": "34:38"
        },
        {
          "title": "Discussion of how age classification of animals is determined without relying on individual birthdays, using seasonal births instead",
          "display_title": "Age Counting",
          "timestamp": "35:40"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Mixed Meat Pieces and the Principle of Eating According to the Strictest Rule",
      "display_title": "Mixed Pieces",
      "timestamp": "36:33",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Mishna: when pieces of meat or korbanot with different eating restrictions mix, they are consumed according to the strictest category (kechamur shabahen)",
          "display_title": "Strictest Rule",
          "timestamp": "36:33"
        },
        {
          "title": "Discussion of Rabbi Shimon's view and the objection that mixed korbanot should not be brought (ein mevivin kodashim l'veis hapsul) for fear of leftovers",
          "display_title": "Leftovers Concern",
          "timestamp": "36:33"
        },
        {
          "title": "Resolution: for already-cut meat, the concern about nosar is outweighed by practical necessity, supporting Rabbi Shimon's lenient approach",
          "display_title": "Practical Override",
          "timestamp": "37:38"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
